    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ecd7fc5d-fbc2-43c0-8687-a6a73bb4bd68",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 39-year-old male who presents with a disheveled and unkempt appearance — his clothes are mismatched, his hair uncombed, and he carries a faint odor suggesting infrequent personal hygiene. He makes intermittent eye contact and sits rigidly during the interview, occasionally tilting his head as though listening to something in the room. His speech is tangential and sometimes loosely associated; he shifts abruptly from discussing neighborhood surveillance to recounting fragments of dreams and abstract philosophical musings.\n\n{patientName} has been living in a subsidized apartment in an urban neighborhood for the past four years, after previously cycling through his mother's home and several short-term shelters. He spends most of his days indoors, seldom leaving except to purchase food or cigarettes from a nearby corner store. He smokes approximately one pack of cigarettes per day and has a history of cannabis use, which he reports using \"to calm the noise.\" He drinks alcohol occasionally — usually cheap beer — and denies current use of illicit stimulants.\n\nPrior to the onset of his illness, {patientName} worked as a warehouse inventory clerk and had a close-knit group of friends from his high school days. He describes those years as \"the last time I felt normal.\" He briefly attended a community college but dropped out after his first episode of psychosis at age 22. He has had no sustained employment for over a decade. He spends time drawing intricate geometric patterns, which he says represent \"the structures only he can see,\" and occasionally watches television with the volume turned low.\n\nSocially, {patientName} has very limited relationships. He has a strained but persistent connection with his mother, who calls him weekly and occasionally brings groceries. He has no romantic partner and reports never having had a long-term relationship. He has one younger brother who lives out of state and with whom contact is rare. His case manager visits him biweekly and has been instrumental in keeping him engaged with the mental health system.\n\nDuring the current visit, {patientName} reports increased auditory hallucinations over the last three weeks — voices that comment on his actions and occasionally issue commands. He endorses a delusional belief that a local utility company has installed monitoring devices in his walls and that his thoughts are being \"extracted\" at night. He denies active suicidal ideation but appears to have significant affective blunting and anhedonia. His insight into his illness remains very limited."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
